Thermodynamic Drag Framework: Entropy-Constrained, Infrastructure-Coupled Dynamics

A Control-Theoretic, Information-Geometric, and Thermodynamic Research Program for Recursive Systems

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Version: 1.1 — Final PhD Manuscript
Date: April 9, 2026

---

Abstract

We present the Thermodynamic Drag Framework (TDF), a rigorous mathematical formalism for analyzing recursive systems—including potentially self-improving artificial intelligences—as physical processes governed by the laws of thermodynamics, information geometry, and control theory. The framework posits that any system capable of recursive self-modification operates within a bounded region of a state manifold defined by its complexity, energy, entropy, and information density. Stability is equivalent to thermodynamic closure under finite resource constraints.

We define the Thermodynamic Drag Tensor, which quantifies the excess entropy production beyond the Landauer bound, and derive the Ames–Maakoul Limit, an upper bound on the rate of complexity growth dictated by entropy export capacity. A bifurcation analysis of the coupled feedback equations yields the dimensionless Maakoul Number (Mk), a predictive threshold for thermal runaway or collapse. We introduce the Fisher‑refined Viability Kernel, which ensures that a system retains sufficient self‑awareness to navigate its thermodynamic landscape. The framework further proposes a modified Ricci flow as a geometric model for recursive self‑optimization and identifies a candidate Triple Point—a coordinate of maximum sustainable recursion. A fully worked toy model illustrates the application of these concepts.

This work does not claim to establish new physical laws. Rather, it synthesizes established results from stochastic thermodynamics, information geometry, and dynamical systems into a unified, testable research program. By clearly distinguishing definitions, hypotheses, propositions, and theorems, and by providing dimensional analyses and explicit assumptions, the TDF aims to serve as a foundation for the rigorous engineering and governance of advanced recursive systems.

