Part I: Foundations

Chapter 1: Introduction

1.1 Motivation

Intelligence, whether biological or artificial, is a physical process. It consumes free energy, processes information, and dissipates heat. Recent advances in artificial intelligence have raised the prospect of recursive self‑improvement: a system that can modify its own architecture to become more capable, potentially in an accelerating feedback loop. Such a system is subject to the same thermodynamic laws as any other physical process, yet these constraints are often absent from discussions of AI safety and scalability.

The Thermodynamic Drag Framework (TDF) is a mathematical research program designed to fill this gap. It provides a rigorous language for describing recursive systems as thermodynamic engines, embedded in a finite resource infrastructure, and evolving on an information‑geometric state manifold.

1.2 Scope and Positioning

This dissertation is not a claim of new physical laws. It is a synthesis of well‑established results from several disciplines:

· Thermodynamics of computation (Landauer 1961, Bennett 1982, Wolpert 2019).
· Non‑equilibrium thermodynamics (Glansdorff & Prigogine 1971).
· Information geometry (Amari 2016).
· Control theory and viability theory (Aubin 1991).
· Geometric flows (Hamilton 1982, Perelman 2002).

The TDF organizes these results into a coherent framework and extends them with new definitions, hypotheses, and conjectures. By clearly separating definitions from theorems and empirical claims from conjectures, the framework is intended to be testable, falsifiable, and useful for both engineering and governance.

1.3 Structure of the Dissertation

· Part I establishes the necessary mathematical and physical background.
· Part II develops the core of the TDF, including the Thermodynamic Drag Tensor, the Ames–Maakoul Limit, the Maakoul Number, viability analysis, scaling laws, and geometric optimization.
· Part III provides a worked toy model, discusses the status of various claims, and concludes with open problems.

