Chapter 2: Mathematical and Physical Preliminaries

2.1 Thermodynamics of Computation

Theorem 2.1 (Landauer's Principle). Any logically irreversible manipulation of one bit of information must dissipate at least $k_B T \ln 2$ of heat into an environment at temperature $T$, where $k_B$ is the Boltzmann constant.

Proof. See Landauer (1961). The proof uses the fact that erasing one bit halves the number of accessible microstates, requiring an entropy increase of at least $k_B \ln 2$ in the environment to satisfy the Second Law. ∎

Corollary 2.1 (Minimum Entropy Generation). The rate of entropy generation due to irreversible bit erasures is bounded below by
\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{comp}} \ge k_B \ln 2 \cdot \dot{I}_{\text{erased}},


where $\dot{I}_{\text{erased}}$ is the rate at which bits are erased.

2.2 Information Geometry

Definition 2.1 (Fisher Information Metric). Let $p(x \mid \theta)$ be a family of probability distributions parameterized by $\theta \in \Theta$. The Fisher Information Metric is the Riemannian metric on $\Theta$ given by
g_{ij}^F(\theta) = \int p(x \mid \theta) \frac{\partial \log p}{\partial \theta^i} \frac{\partial \log p}{\partial \theta^j} \, dx = \mathbb{E}_\theta\left[ \frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \theta^i} \frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \theta^j} \right],


where $\ell = \log p$.

This metric quantifies the distinguishability of nearby parameter values: the geodesic distance $d(\theta_1, \theta_2)$ is related to the minimum thermodynamic work required to move between the corresponding thermodynamic states (Crooks 2007).

2.3 Stochastic Thermodynamics

We adopt the framework of stochastic thermodynamics (Seifert 2012), which extends thermodynamic concepts to small, fluctuating systems. A system coupled to a thermal bath evolves according to a Langevin or master equation, and quantities like work, heat, and entropy production are defined at the level of individual trajectories.

Fluctuation Theorem (Crooks 1999). For a system driven out of equilibrium, the probability $P_F(W)$ of observing work $W$ along a forward trajectory and the probability $P_R(-W)$ of observing work $-W$ along the reverse trajectory satisfy
\frac{P_F(W)}{P_R(-W)} = \exp\left( \frac{W - \Delta F}{k_B T} \right),


where $\Delta F$ is the free energy difference between initial and final states.

2.4 Bifurcation Theory: The Bogdanov–Takens Normal Form

A Bogdanov–Takens bifurcation occurs in a dynamical system when a fixed point has a double‑zero eigenvalue. Its normal form is
\begin{aligned} \dot{x} &= y, \\ \dot{y} &= \mu_1 + \mu_2 x + x^2 \pm xy. \end{aligned}


This bifurcation serves as an organizing center for saddle‑node, Hopf, and homoclinic bifurcations (Kuznetsov 2004).

2.5 Viability Theory

Definition 2.2 (Viability Kernel). Given a dynamical system $\dot{\Xi} = f(\Xi, u, d)$ with controls $u \in U$ and disturbances $d \in D$, the viability kernel $\text{Viab}_f(K)$ of a compact set $K \subset \mathcal{M}$ is the largest subset of $K$ such that for every initial state in the kernel, there exists a measurable control policy $u(t) \in U$ that keeps the trajectory inside $K$ for all $t \ge 0$ and for all admissible disturbances $d(t) \in D$.

