Part II: The Core Framework

Chapter 3: The Thermodynamic Drag Tensor and Effective Metric

3.1 State Manifold and the Fisher Metric

Definition 3.1 (State Manifold). The state of a recursive system is described by a point $\Xi = (S, I, E, \Sigma)$ on the differentiable manifold $\mathcal{M} = \mathbb{R}^+ \times \mathbb{R}^+ \times \mathbb{R}^+ \times \mathbb{R}^+$. We equip $\mathcal{M}$ with the Fisher Information Metric $g_{\mu\nu}^F$ derived from the statistical distinguishability of thermodynamic states.

Assumption 3.1 (Fisher Metric Exists). There exists a physically meaningful family of probability distributions $p(\text{microstate} \mid \Xi)$ such that $g_{\mu\nu}^F$ is well‑defined and positive definite.

3.2 The Thermodynamic Drag Tensor

Definition 3.2 (Thermodynamic Drag Tensor). The Thermodynamic Drag Tensor $\Gamma_{\mu\nu}(\Xi)$ is a symmetric, positive semi‑definite tensor field on $\mathcal{M}$ that accounts for all sources of excess dissipation beyond the Landauer bound.

Definition 3.3 (Effective Metric). The effective metric for the thermodynamic cost of state transitions is
g_{\mu\nu}^{\text{eff}}(\Xi) = g_{\mu\nu}^F(\Xi) + \Gamma_{\mu\nu}(\Xi).

Definition 3.4 (Drag Coefficient). The scalar Drag Coefficient is
\Gamma(\Xi) = 1 + \frac{1}{\dim \mathcal{M}} \text{Tr}\left( (g^F)^{-1} \Gamma \right).


For $\Gamma_{\mu\nu} = 0$, we have $\Gamma = 1$, corresponding to reversible computation at the Landauer limit.

Physical Interpretation. The additional term $\Gamma_{\mu\nu}$ makes state transitions "longer" in the effective metric, meaning more thermodynamic work is required. This is the geometric manifestation of the Landauer Gap.

3.3 Work and Entropy Production Along a Path

Proposition 3.1 (Work Along a Path). The minimum thermodynamic work required to move the system along a path $\gamma : [0,1] \to \mathcal{M}$ is
W_{\text{min}}(\gamma) = \int_\gamma \sqrt{ g_{\mu\nu}^{\text{eff}} \, d\Xi^\mu d\Xi^\nu }.


The actual work satisfies $W_{\text{actual}} \ge W_{\text{min}}$.

Proof. This follows from the standard formulation of thermodynamic length (Crooks 2007) combined with the effective metric. ∎

Corollary 3.1 (Landauer Bound with Drag). The rate of heat dissipation due to irreversible bit erasures is
\dot{Q} \ge k_B T \ln 2 \cdot \Gamma(\Xi) \cdot \dot{I}_{\text{erased}}.

