Chapter 4: System Dynamics and the Recursive Operator

4.1 Resource and Maintenance Costs

Definition 4.1 (Resource Vector). The resource vector is $R(t) = (E_{\text{avail}}(t), W(t), L(t))$.

Definition 4.2 (Maintenance Cost). The maintenance power $\mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)$ is the rate of energy consumption required to sustain a given complexity $S$ without any growth.

Assumption 4.1 (Monotonic Maintenance). $\mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)$ is a strictly increasing, convex function of $S$.

4.2 The Recursive Operator

Definition 4.3 (Autocatalytic Efficiency). The autocatalytic efficiency $\alpha(S) \in [0,1]$ is the fraction of available free energy that can be successfully converted into increased complexity. We assume $\alpha'(S) \le 0$, reflecting increasing coordination overhead.

Definition 4.4 (Recursive Operator). The rate of change of complexity is
\dot{S} = \mathcal{R}(S, R) = \alpha(S) \cdot \frac{\mathcal{G}(R,S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)}{\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S)},


where $\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S)$ is the specific energy cost to increase complexity by one unit (J/bit).

Proposition 4.1 (Complexity Wall). A necessary condition for $\dot{S} > 0$ is
\mathcal{G}(R,S) > \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S).


The surface $\mathcal{G} = \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}$ defines the Complexity Wall, a practical limit on unassisted recursion.

4.3 Full Dynamical System

The coupled dynamics are:
\begin{aligned}
\dot{S} &= \mathcal{R}(S, R), \\
\dot{E} &= \mathcal{G}(R,S) - \mathcal{T}(C,T) - \mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S) \dot{S}, \\
\frac{d\Sigma}{dt} &= \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} - \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}},
\end{aligned}


subject to the dissipation constraint $\mathcal{T}(C,T) \ge k_B T \ln 2 \cdot \Gamma(\Xi) \cdot \dot{I}$.

