Chapter 5: Entropy Bounds and the Ames–Maakoul Limit

5.1 Derivation of the Limit

Assumption 5.1 (Irreversibility of Complexity Growth). Any increase in algorithmic complexity $S$ requires the erasure of a proportional amount of information, so that
\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{comp}} = \kappa^{-1} \dot{S},


where $\kappa$ is a constant with units bits / (J/K).

Theorem 5.1 (Ames–Maakoul Limit). Under Assumption 5.1, the rate of complexity growth is bounded by the entropy export capacity:
\dot{S} \le \kappa \cdot \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}.

Proof. The total entropy generation rate is $\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} = \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{comp}} + \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{infra}} \ge \kappa^{-1} \dot{S}$. For long‑term stability, the time‑averaged entropy balance requires $\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} \le \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}$. Thus $\kappa^{-1} \dot{S} \le \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}$, giving the result. ∎

Corollary 5.1 (Extended Limit with Latency). Including the speed‑of‑light constraint on coordination across spatial extent $L$, we have
\dot{S} \le \min\left( \kappa \cdot \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}, \; \frac{\eta_{\text{comm}} \cdot c \cdot B}{L} \right),


where $B$ is bandwidth and $\eta_{\text{comm}}$ is communication efficiency.

