Chapter 6: Bifurcation Analysis and the Maakoul Number

6.1 The S‑I‑R Feedback Equations

We consider the coupled system between Intelligence $I$ and Negentropy $N$:
\begin{aligned}
\dot{I} &= \sigma(I, N) I - \epsilon \dot{I} - \delta(T) I, \\
\dot{N} &= \dot{N}_{\text{in}} - \sigma(I, N) I,
\end{aligned}


where $\sigma(I,N)$ is the metabolic gate, $\epsilon \dot{I}$ is the Landauer cost, and $\delta(T) I$ is the maintenance tax.

6.2 Reduction to Bogdanov–Takens Normal Form

Assumption 6.1 (B‑T Reduction). Near a critical operating point, the S‑I‑R system can be reduced, via center manifold theory, to the Bogdanov–Takens normal form.

Proposition 6.1. Under Assumption 6.1, the local dynamics are governed by
\begin{aligned}
\dot{x} &= y, \\
\dot{y} &= \mu_1 + \mu_2 x + x^2 \pm xy,
\end{aligned}


where $x$ is a scaled temperature deviation and the parameters are
\mu_1 = \frac{\mathcal{G} - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}}{\text{scale}_1}, \quad \mu_2 = \frac{\Gamma(\Xi) - 1}{\text{scale}_2}.

6.3 The Maakoul Number

Definition 6.1 (Maakoul Number). The Maakoul Number is the dimensionless quantity
\text{Mk} = \frac{\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}}}{\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}} \cdot \frac{\mathcal{T}(C,T)}{\mathcal{G}(R,S)} \cdot \Gamma(\Xi).

Theorem 6.1 (Collapse Threshold). Under Assumption 6.1, the condition $\text{Mk} > 1$ is a sufficient condition for the system to be in the runaway region of the bifurcation diagram, where no stable fixed point or limit cycle exists, leading to thermal collapse or energy depletion.

Proof. By expressing $\mu_1$ and $\mu_2$ in terms of the physical parameters, one finds that $\text{Mk} > 1$ corresponds to a point beyond the homoclinic bifurcation curve in the $(\mu_1, \mu_2)$ plane. Trajectories in this region escape to infinity (infinite temperature or zero energy). ∎

