Chapter 7: Viability Theory and the Fisher‑Refined Kernel

7.1 Viability Constraints

Definition 7.1 (Admissible Set). The system must satisfy the following constraints at all times:

· Energy: $E \ge E_{\min}$,
· Entropy: $\Sigma \le \Sigma_{\max}$,
· Drag: $\Gamma(\Xi) \le \Gamma_{\max}$,
· Fisher Information: $\det(g_{\mu\nu}^F) \ge \theta_{\min}$.

The last condition ensures the system retains sufficient self‑awareness to navigate the state space.

Definition 7.2 (Fisher‑Refined Viability Kernel).
K_F = \left\{ \Xi \in \mathcal{M} \mid E \ge E_{\min},\; \Sigma \le \Sigma_{\max},\; \Gamma \le \Gamma_{\max},\; \det(g^F) \ge \theta_{\min} \right\}.

7.2 Hamilton–Jacobi–Isaacs Characterization

Theorem 7.1 (HJI Equation for the Kernel). The viability kernel $K_F$ is the zero sublevel set of the viscosity solution $V(\Xi)$ to the Hamilton–Jacobi–Isaacs equation:
\min_{u \in U} \max_{d \in D} \left[ \nabla V \cdot f(\Xi, u, d) \right] = 0,


with boundary condition $V(\Xi) = 0$ on $\partial K_F$.

Proof. See Aubin (1991) and Bardi & Capuzzo‑Dolcetta (1997). ∎

