Chapter 9: Scaling Laws and the Complexity Wall

9.1 TDF Scaling Hypothesis

Hypothesis 9.1 (Scaling of Energy with Complexity). For a given architecture, the required free energy supply rate scales with complexity as
\mathcal{G}(R,S) \propto S^\beta,


where $\beta$ is the scaling exponent.

· $\beta < 1$: sublinear, scalable.
· $\beta = 1$: linear.
· $\beta > 1$: superlinear, unsustainable at large scale.

Empirical Claim 9.1. Measurements of AI training runs suggest $\beta \approx 1.2$–$1.4$ for current transformer architectures (Kaplan et al. 2020; Hoffmann et al. 2022).

9.2 Thermodynamic‑Complexity Duality

Following Neukart & Vinokur (2025), we write an extended first law:
dE = T d\Sigma - p dV + \mu dN + \lambda dC,


where $C$ is a complexity measure (e.g., circuit depth) and $\lambda$ is the "algorithmic tension."

Proposition 9.1 (Algorithmic Wall). Growth is also bounded by
\lambda \cdot \dot{C} \le \mathcal{G}(R,S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S).

