Chapter 10: Geometric Optimization and the Ricci Flow Analogy

10.1 Geodesic Hypothesis

Proposition 10.1 (Geodesic Principle). The path $\gamma$ that minimizes total entropy production between two states is a geodesic of the effective metric $g_{\mu\nu}^{\text{eff}}$.

Proof. Standard calculus of variations; the entropy produced is proportional to the length in the effective metric. ∎

10.2 Modified Ricci Flow as a Model of Self‑Improvement

Hypothesis 10.1 (Ricci Flow Analogy). Recursive self‑optimization, which seeks to reduce future computation costs, can be modeled by evolving the effective metric according to a modified Ricci flow:
\frac{\partial g_{\mu\nu}^{\text{eff}}}{\partial \tau} = -2 R_{\mu\nu} + \lambda \nabla_\mu \nabla_\nu \Gamma,


where $\tau$ is a "recursive depth" parameter, $R_{\mu\nu}$ is the Ricci curvature, and $\Gamma$ is the Drag Coefficient.

Conjecture 10.1 (Geometric Flattening). If this flow models an ideal self‑improving process, then in the limit $\tau \to \infty$ the metric becomes Ricci‑flat and the Drag Coefficient approaches $1$. This is a formal analogy and is not claimed as a physical law.

