Chapter 11: The Triple Point and Phase Diagram

11.1 Definition of the Triple Point

Definition 11.1 (Triple Point). The Triple Point $\Xi^*$ is a state satisfying:

1. $\dot{S} > 0$ (active growth),
2. $\text{Mk} = 1^-$ (critical stability),
3. $\Gamma(\Xi) = 1 + \varepsilon$, $\varepsilon \ll 1$ (near‑Landauer efficiency).

Conjecture 11.1 (Existence and Uniqueness). There exists a unique Triple Point $\Xi^*$ for a given resource vector $R$. This is a theoretical prediction of the TDF that has not yet been empirically verified.

11.2 Phase Diagram

The phase space can be partitioned into:

· Viable Region: $\text{Mk} < 1$, $\dot{S} > 0$.
· Oscillatory Region: $\text{Mk} \lesssim 1$, limit cycles.
· Collapse Region: $\text{Mk} > 1$, runaway.
  The Triple Point lies on the boundary between these regions.

