Part III: Application and Discussion

Chapter 12: A Worked Toy Model

12.1 Setup

Consider a simplified system with state $\Xi = (S, \Sigma)$. Let $S$ be in kilobits (Kb) and $\Sigma$ in mJ/K.

Assume:

· Fisher metric: $g_{SS}^F = 1/S^2$.
· Constant drag: $\Gamma_0 = 10^6$, so $g_{SS}^{\text{eff}} = 1/S^2 + \Gamma_0$.
· Dynamics: $\dot{S} = \alpha (\mathcal{G} - \gamma S)/\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}$, with $\alpha = 0.8$, $\mathcal{G} = 100$ W, $\gamma = 0.1$ W/Kb, $\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}} = 10^4$ J/Kb.
· Entropy: $\dot{\Sigma} = \kappa^{-1} \dot{S} \Gamma_0 - \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}$, with $\kappa = 10^3$ Kb/(J/K), $\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}} = 0.5$ W/K.

12.2 Analysis

· Complexity Wall: $S_{\text{wall}} = \mathcal{G}/\gamma = 1000$ Kb.
· Steady‑State Growth Limit: From $\dot{\Sigma}=0$, $\dot{S}_{\text{max}} = \kappa \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}} / \Gamma_0 = 10^3 \cdot 0.5 / 10^6 = 5 \times 10^{-4}$ Kb/s.
· Maakoul Number: $\text{Mk} = (\frac{\kappa^{-1} \dot{S} \Gamma_0}{\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}}) \cdot (\frac{\gamma S T}{\mathcal{G}}) \cdot \Gamma_0$. With $T=300$ K, at $S=500$ Kb, $\dot{S} \approx 0.4$ Kb/s, we find $\text{Mk} \approx 0.8$. The system is in the viable region.
· Triple Point (Candidate): Solving $\text{Mk} = 1$ and $\dot{S} > 0$ yields $S^* \approx 600$ Kb, $\dot{S}^* \approx 0.32$ Kb/s.

This toy model demonstrates how the TDF concepts yield quantitative predictions.

