Chapter 13: Empirical Claims, Hypotheses, and Conjectures

13.1 Empirical Claims (Testable with Current Technology)

· Claim 1 (Drag Coefficient): $\Gamma$ for a given chip can be estimated by measuring energy per bit erasure and comparing to $k_B T \ln 2$. For CMOS, $\Gamma \sim 10^9$ (Murray 2025).
· Claim 2 (Scaling Exponent): $\beta$ can be measured for AI models by fitting $\mathcal{G}$ vs. parameter count.

13.2 Hypotheses (Plausible but Requiring Further Validation)

· Hypothesis 1 (Effective Metric): The thermodynamic cost of state transitions is well‑modeled by $g^{\text{eff}} = g^F + \Gamma$.
· Hypothesis 2 (B‑T Reduction): The S‑I‑R system exhibits a Bogdanov–Takens bifurcation near criticality.

13.3 Conjectures (Long‑Term Theoretical Directions)

· Conjecture 1 (Triple Point Existence): A unique $\Xi^*$ exists.
· Conjecture 2 (Ricci Flow Mechanism): Advanced recursive self‑improvement will be isomorphic to a geometric flow.

